<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-417-830  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 417 830.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  June 21 1989 v18 n8 p28(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Getting a handle on FDDI. (fiber distributed data interchange)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Thurber, Kenneth J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) standard is rapidlyevolving but may not satisfy all future needs.andP;  FDDI is based ondual counter-rotating token rings operating at 100 M-bps.andP;  It usestwo strands of optical fiber powered by 1300-nanometer LEDs andvarious methods of physical attachment depending on theapplication.andP;  The FDDI standard is very close to finalization andimplementation.andP;  Three of its four layers have been solidlyapproved by ANSI, with only Station Management remaining.andP;  FDDI islikely to find an immediate application niche, but in the long runwill prove lacking in adequate bandwidth as users' needs grow.andO;Expanded use of high-powered microcomputers and workstations willcontinue to cause bottlenecks in future networks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber Distributed Data Interface StandardFuture TechnologiesLocal Area NetworksStandardsBandwidthFiber Optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Three of the four FDDI protocols are virtually standards (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>